reviewText: I hear that the High Kings will be the opening act for Celtic Woman's tour...that would be a star-studded evening for sure.  I can't say enough about this DVD:  handsome, full-voiced Irishmen who love their country and its history - who bring so much musical talent individually to this group and who love to get the audience fully involved in each beautiful number. I find myself happily humming their tunes over and over in my head.  David Downes has done another fantastic job at the helm of this wonderful project.
summary: Clap your hands and tap your feet!

reviewText: I LOVE celtic music!!  (How anyone can NOT like it is hard for me to understand!)  And this DVD featuring the musically talented sons of some of Ireland's all-time favorite performers is a great way to enjoy it. Backed up by a very talented group of musicians, and recorded before an enthusiastic LIVE audience, the High Kings present a high-tempo trip through Irish music with a wonderfully varied selection of song which includes both familiar favorites and some lesser known gems. If you like Irish/Celtic music, or if you've yet to discover it's charm and power, you'll find yourself enthralled by these very talented and enthusiastic young men!!  I own several dozen CDs and DVDs of Irish and Scottish music. This is one of the very best!!

reviewText: I wasn't expecting too much from this new group despite the considerable hype accompanying their new album and DVD.  However, I am a longtime listener to Irish music of most types and a particular fan of the Clancys (I'm old enough to have seen the original group), the Irish Rovers, the Dubliners,Wolfe Tones, etc., etc. and I couldn't resist checking out these young heirs to the throne (3 of the 4 are sons of famous Irish singing families).  I am happy to say that I was not only pleasantly surprised--I was blown away.  All of these singers are actually outstanding musicians and their harmonies are beautiful.  Their choice of well-known Irish ballads, rousing sing-along-melodies and poignant songs reflecting Ireland's history is an excellent one and I hope they do not stray from this type of mix.  They bring the wonderful old Irish songs made popular world-wide by their parents' generation to a new generation in a slick effective package put together by the man behind Celtic Woman. Fortunately he stops just short of over-producing these guys, who do not need any more enhancement than they have in this DVD.  They have powerful voices and tremendous musicianship and they are definitely NOT Celtic Man--they are the new flowering of a great Irish folk tradition, packaged very neatly but basically true to that tradition.  I hope they stay that way and put out lots more albums and DVDs.  The High Kings are a find!
summary: Dynamite New Irish Group Unites Generations

reviewText: If you love Irish music this is for you. It matters not if you do not have a drop of Irish blood in your veins, The High Kings will stir your spirit and soul with their traditional Irish tunes.  The harmony is superb and the songs will make you sing along or at least tap your feet and clap your hands. America may not be familar with this group - I know I wasn't until I found a copy of their CD at my local library.  I was hooked.  This selection is more than worth the money and a pure pleasure to listen to.  I hope we hear more from these lads.

reviewText: Nothing to add really to all the glowing reviews here. I first heard them on a St Patricks Day special on TV and immediately bought the CD. The harmonies have the rich layers of the old Crosby Stills and Nash days but done in the Irish style that is foot-stomping, mournful, reflective, spiritual and ultimately triumphant. Just an incredible CD, you won't be disappointed.

reviewText: I've owned this dvd for about 2 weeks now, and have watched it several times already.  These guys have wonderful voices and energy, and I am nowhere close to being tired of their music.  As a person who usually finds 1 or 2 songs that they dislike from a cd or dvd, I love every single one of their songs, and the band is awesome.  If you like Irish folk music, you will definitely love this.  Also, unlike Celtic Woman and Celtic Thunder, the set is not over-the-top and hasn't been overproduced.  I highly recommend this dvd!

reviewText: Great Celtic music and great entertainment! The High Kings voices, their music selection and their on stage presentation style are exceptional. Added to this is that the DVD producer actually kept the audio mixing in balance so you can hear the actual voice tracks without much reverb, distortion and heavy background music. Thank you producer, very much. Both the video quality and the audio recording quality are also excellent. So sit back, sip a wee bit of Irish whiskey, relax, crank up the volume a little and enjoy Irish music at its finest!

reviewText: I first saw The High Kings on their PBS special, (much like Celtic Woman, with whom I'm also very enamored), and from the opening number, "Rocky Road To Dublin", I knew I had to get the DVD.  The product itself is pretty ordinary.  No behind the scenes or anything like that.  Just the concert, and the rather handy option of subtitles, since some of the lyrics either go by so fast you can't keep up or are in Gaelic, or both.  But the concert MORE than makes up for the lack of bells & whistles.The production is somewhat smaller than Celtic Woman, which is actually quite nice, giving the show a more intimate quality, and they communicate with the audience well.  The singers of the group all are fantastic vocalists, showcasing tight harmonies, rousing pub tunes, as well as inspired and touching ballads, all traditional Irish songs.  Of particular note is the backup band, particularly the madly talented percussionist.  He plays the bodhran like nothing I've ever seen, and is even showcased with a brief solo, followed by a duet with another insanely talented Irish tap dancer, you've gotta see this!The only resemblance that I can see between The High Kings and Celtic Woman is the fantastically talented performers.  Though both acts are undeniably Irish, they're also apples and oranges.  Where Celtic Woman leans more towards New Age, Contemporary and even classical, The High Kings are purely traditional Irish, in the realm of The Clancy Brothers, The Dubliners, and The Irish Rovers.So get the DVD, pour yourself a good Irish stout, sit back and push play!
